---
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import PNotes from "../components/PNotes.astro";
import underTheHood from "../img/under-the-hood.webp";
---

<p-slide class="center" autoplay timing="550">
  <h1 class="main-gradient">MCP under the hood</h1>
  <p-fragment
    ><Image
      src={underTheHood}
      alt="MCP under the hood"
      class="alter-image-size"
      style="border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid"
    /></p-fragment
  >
</p-slide>
<p-slide class="center">
  <h2 class="main-sub-gradient">JSON-RPC</h2>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      JSON-RPC is a lightweight protocol for calling functions on another system
      using JSON messages. It allows MCP to send requests to connected services
      and receive responses in a standardized format, making it easier to
      integrate with a wide variety of APIs and systems.
    </p>
    <p>
      MCP uses JSON-RPC as the communication protocol between the AI and the
      connected services. JSON-RPC is a simple, stateless, and lightweight
      remote procedure call (RPC) protocol that uses JSON as its data format.
    </p>

    <p>
      This choice allows MCP to be flexible and compatible with a wide range of
      services and programming languages, as JSON is widely supported and easy
      to work with.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>
<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">JSON-RPC - request</span> 🔧
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="example-request.json">
<code style="line-height: 1.2" is:raw class="language-javascript">
    {
      "jsonrpc": "2.0",
      "id": 1,
      "method": "tools/call",
      "params": {
        "name": "getOrders",
        "arguments": {
          "customerId": "123"
        }
      }
    }</code>
   </pre>
</p-slide>
<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">JSON-RPC - response</span> 🔧
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="example-response.json">
<code style="line-height: 1.2" is:raw class="language-javascript">
    {
      "jsonrpc": "2.0",
      "id": 1,
      "result": {
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Found 3 pending orders."
          }
        ]
      }
    }</code>
   </pre>
</p-slide>
<p-slide>
  <h2 class="main-gradient">Why does this matter?</h2>

  <ul>
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        📌 Messages are <span class="main-sub-gradient">structured</span>
      </li></p-fragment
    >
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        📌 Inputs can be <span class="main-sub-gradient">validated</span>
      </li></p-fragment
    >
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        📌 Errors are <span class="main-sub-gradient">predictable</span>
      </li></p-fragment
    >
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        📌 Integrations are <span class="main-sub-gradient">simpler</span>
      </li></p-fragment
    >
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        📌 Development is <span class="main-sub-gradient">faster</span>
      </li></p-fragment
    >
  </ul>
</p-slide>
<p-slide class="center">
  <h2 class="main-gradient">Capabilities</h2>
  <span style="font-size: 8rem">🤹</span>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      MCP provides a set of capabilities that allow AI models to interact with
      external systems in a structured and predictable way. These capabilities
      include:
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>
<p-slide data-capabilities autoplay timing="700">
  <p-fragment p-effect="zoom" timing-start="700"><p>🧰 Tools</p></p-fragment>
  <p-fragment p-effect="zoom" timing-start="1100"
    ><p>📦 Resources</p></p-fragment
  >
  <p-fragment p-effect="insert" timing-start="1500"
    ><p>💬 Prompts</p></p-fragment
  >
</p-slide>
<p-slide>
  <h2>🧰 <span class="main-gradient">Tools</span></h2>
  <ul style="
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 1em;
">
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        ✍🏻 Functions that the AI can <span class="main-sub-gradient"
          >invoke</span
        > on a connected server
      </li></p-fragment
    >
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        📝 Each tool exposes a <span class="main-sub-gradient">name</span>, a <span
          class="main-sub-gradient">description</span
        > and an
        <span class="main-sub-gradient">input schema</span>
      </li></p-fragment
    >
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        🏆 Results are returned as <span class="main-sub-gradient"
          >structured content</span
        >
      </li></p-fragment
    >
  </ul>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Tools are the most commonly used MCP capability. They let the AI model
      call functions defined on the server — for example, fetching data,
      triggering actions, or querying external APIs. The server declares each
      tool with a name, a human-readable description, and a JSON Schema that
      defines the expected input. The model reads these declarations and decides
      on its own when it makes sense to call a tool and with which arguments.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Tools - definition</span> 🧰
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="server.ts">
<code is:raw class="language-typescript">  
  server.tool(
    "getOrders",
    "Returns pending orders for a customer",
    { customerId: z.string() },
    async ({ customerId }) => ({
      content: [
        { type: "text", text: `Found 3 pending orders.` }
      ],
    })
  );</code>
  </pre>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Tools - call</span> 🧰
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    style="line-height: 1.2"
    data-label-file="tool-call.json">
<code is:raw class="language-javascript">
  {
    "jsonrpc": "2.0",
    "id": 2,
    "method": "tools/call",
    "params": {
      "name": "getOrders",
      "arguments": {
        "customerId": "123"
      }
    }
}</code></pre>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Tools - response</span> 🧰
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="tool-response.json">
<code style="line-height: 1.2" is:raw class="language-javascript">
  {
    "jsonrpc": "2.0",
    "id": 2,
    "result": {
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Found 3 pending orders."
        }
      ]
    }
  }</code></pre>
</p-slide>
<p-slide>
  <h2>📦 <span class="main-gradient">Resources</span></h2>
  <ul style="
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 1em;
">
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        🗂️ Read-only data the server exposes for the AI to <span
          class="main-sub-gradient">read</span
        >
      </li></p-fragment
    >
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        🔗 Each resource has a <span class="main-sub-gradient">URI</span>, a <span
          class="main-sub-gradient">name</span
        > and an optional
        <span class="main-sub-gradient">MIME type</span>
      </li></p-fragment
    >
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        📄 Content is returned as <span class="main-sub-gradient"
          >text or binary</span
        >
      </li></p-fragment
    >
  </ul>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Resources are the MCP way to expose data sources to the AI model. Unlike
      tools, resources are read-only — the server declares them and the AI can
      request their content. A resource is identified by a URI (e.g.
      orders://pending) and can return text or binary content along with a MIME
      type. Resources are ideal for exposing documents, database records, or any
      static or semi-static data the model needs to reason about.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Resources - definition</span> 📦
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="server.ts">
<code style="line-height: 1.2" is:raw class="language-typescript">
  server.resource(
    "orders://pending",
    "Returns the list of pending orders",
    async (uri) => ({
      contents: [
        {
          uri: uri.href,
          mimeType: "text/plain",
          text: "Order #1\nOrder #2\nOrder #3",
        },
      ],
    })
  );</code></pre>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Resources - read</span> 📦
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    style="line-height: 1.2"
    data-label-file="resource-read.json">
<code is:raw class="language-javascript">
  {
    "jsonrpc": "2.0",
    "id": 3,
    "method": "resources/read",
    "params": {
      "uri": "orders://pending"
    }
  }
</code>
</pre>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Resources - response</span> 📦
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="resource-response.json">
<code style="line-height: 1.2" is:raw class="language-javascript">
  {
    "jsonrpc": "2.0",
    "id": 3,
    "result": {
      "contents": [
        {
          "uri": "orders://pending",
          "mimeType": "text/plain",
          "text": "Order #1\nOrder #2\nOrder #3"
        }
      ]
    }
  }</code></pre>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h2>💬 <span class="main-gradient">Prompts</span></h2>
  <ul style="
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 1em;
">
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        📋 Pre-defined message templates the server <span
          class="main-sub-gradient">exposes</span
        > to clients
      </li></p-fragment
    >
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        🔧 They accept <span class="main-sub-gradient">arguments</span> to generate
        dynamic messages
      </li></p-fragment
    >
    <p-fragment
      ><li>
        🤖 Results are returned as a list of <span class="main-sub-gradient"
          >messages</span
        >
      </li></p-fragment
    >
  </ul>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Prompts are reusable message templates declared by the server. Unlike
      tools — which the AI calls autonomously — prompts are surfaced to the
      client or user interface, which can then inject them into the
      conversation. Each prompt can accept arguments to produce dynamic,
      parameterized messages.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Prompts - definition</span> 💬
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="server.ts">
<code style="line-height: 1.2; font-size: 1.2rem" is:raw class="language-typescript">
  server.prompt(
    "customer-support",
    "Generates a support context for a customer",
    { customerId: z.string() },
    async ({ customerId }) => ({
      messages: [{
        role: "user",
        content: {
          type: "text",
          text: `Customer ${customerId} needs help.Use the available customer/order tools if needed,
                 then suggest next steps.`,
        },
      }],
    })
  );</code></pre>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Prompts - get</span> 💬
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    style="line-height: 1.2"
    data-label-file="prompt-get.json">
<code is:raw class="language-javascript">
  {
    "jsonrpc": "2.0",
    "id": 4,
    "method": "prompts/get",
    "params": {
      "name": "customer-support",
      "arguments": {
        "customerId": "123"
      }
    }
  }</code>
</pre>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Prompts - response</span> 💬
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="prompt-response.json">
<code style="line-height: 1.2; font-size: 1.4rem" is:raw class="language-javascript">
  {
    "jsonrpc": "2.0",
    "id": 4,
    "result": {
      "messages": [{
        "role": "user",
        "content": {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Customer 123 needs help.\nUse the available customer/order tools if needed,
                   then suggest next steps."
        }
      }]
    }
  }</code></pre>
</p-slide>

<style lang="scss">
  [data-capabilities] p {
    font-size: 4.5rem;
    margin-block: 0.5em;
  }
</style>
